        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Five years ago, on March 11, 2020, the COVID-19 pandemic was <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-15-03-2025-h1-1-declared-a-global-pandemic?source=website" target="_blank">declared a global pandemic</a>. The pandemic reshaped the world in ways it is still grappling with. When travel restrictions were announced and institutions shut down, life was never the same. Over 7 million lives were lost, and it took a profound mental toll on the masses.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Young people miss out on significant amounts of school. Misinformation flourished among people of all ages. It fueled vaccine skepticism and deepened societal divisions. The media landscape shifted, with trust eroding amid political attacks and selective truth. While these issues were already ongoing before the pandemic started, the pandemic put them into overdrive.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Recently, COVID-19 was declared an endemic. The last week of 2024 saw 521 deaths in the US due to this virus. Scientists say long COVID can impact the brain, heart, kidneys, and overall metabolism, which can lead to disablement. With the recent pullout of the US from WHO, the funding for critical research will be limited. While the scientists gave hope of better preparedness for a future pandemic, they mentioned it depends on the nature of the pandemic.</p>
