        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Purim is a Jewish holiday celebrating the transition from <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-15-03-2025-r1-2-subjugation-to-freedom?source=website" target="_blank">subjugation to freedom</a>, similar to Passover and Hanukkah. It commemorates Queen Esther and Mordechai’s triumph over Haman’s plot to annihilate the Jewish people in ancient Persia. The holiday’s name comes from the Hebrew word for “lots.” It refers to Haman’s lottery to determine the massacre date.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Purim emphasizes remembrance, with the Scroll of Esther recounting the story. The festival highlights themes of survival, resilience, and divine intervention. Traditions include reading the Megillah, giving charity, exchanging food gifts, and festive celebrations. Many associate the holiday with Halloween and carnival, and many wear costumes on this day. Historically, Purim has also been linked to later events, such as the Nuremberg trials in 1946.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="0px 12px" />
