          <h2 style="              
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">TikToker jailed in Indonesia for telling Jesus to cut his hair</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Indonesian TikToker Ratu Thalisa, a Muslim transgender woman, was sentenced to nearly <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-15-03-2025-r2-3-three-years-in-prison-for-blasphemy?source=website" target="_blank">three years in prison for blasphemy</a>. She was jokingly telling a picture of Jesus to get a haircut during a livestream. The court ruled her comments disrupted public order following complaints from Christian groups. Amnesty International condemned the verdict as violating free speech while calling for her release.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Many rights groups and activists implore Indonesians to reform its controversial online hate-speech law. Indonesia has some of the strictest anti-blasphemy laws in Asia. They usually disproportionately target religious minorities rather than Muslims, which makes Talia's case unique as she is Muslim. The governor of Jakarta, Ahok, was also found guilty under these laws in 2017.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="0px 12px" />
